Diagnosis. This species can be easily recognized by the presence of a pale (whitish) area in apical part of membrane, distinctly corrugated apex dorsal endosomal sclerite of aedeagus apically, and it can be very easily recognized from the most similar species distributed in Oriental Region (
S. dimidiata
) by the following combination of characters: S-shaped curvature of posterior margin of an eye in lateral view, ridges of proepisternum and proepimeron connected in entire length, metapleura with only one complete ridge and spiracles III–IV placed distant from ventral connexival suture.

eyes glabrous. Dorsal surface of antennifers smooth. Scape club-shaped, with adherent setae and a few erect, robust setae and 2 very long trichobothrial setae (
Fig. 175
). Pedicel, basi- and distiflagellum with dense, adherent, short setae and a few, regularly arranged, erect setae (much smaller on pedicel). Second visible labial segment enlarged basally and reaching posterior margin of eyes. Pronotum with various sized setae. Anterior pronotal lobe with distinct sulci. Lack of collar on anterior pronotal lobe (
Fig. 183
). Apodeme depression of anterior pronotal lobe long and thin. Ridges of proepisternum and proepimeron connected in entire length. Transversal suture of pronotum with slight curvature in middle. Posterior pronotal lobe weakly depressed in middle of anterior margin and delicately sculptured nead transversal furrow. Metapleura with only one complete ridge. Posterior margin of pronotum covered by long setae. Corium with dense setae in basal part of corium and costal margin. Hemelytron various sized, not surpassing or surpassing apex of abdomen in both sexes. Abdomen ventrally with short setae and spiracles III–IV placed distant from ventral connexival suture (
Fig. 185
).

Genitalia
: Male—Pygophore dark brown with paler margin. Median process of pygophore with sharp apex (
Figs. 85, 90
). Both parameres slender in lateral view, slightly arcuate, and apically rounded (
Figs. 86–89
), with sharp process on inner side (
Figs. 86, 88
) Left paramere with small curvature in apical part in dorsal view. Basal lobe of dorsal phallothecal sclerite enlarged on both sides, visibly bigger on right side (
Figs. 91–93
). Dorsal endosomal sclerite distinctly corrugated apically (
Figs. 92, 93
).

Female—Valvifer I rounded (
Fig. 84
), with numerous, small setae and a few distinctly longer setae on outer side. Laterial margins of styloids distinctly curved (
Fig. 82
). Inner margins of styloids rounded with dense, robust setae. Apical part of styloids sharp. Basal part of valvula II with forked process convoluting inwards, apical part with sinuate apex, internal apex sharp, external apex rounded (
Fig. 83
).
